SIMPLE: ply
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ply
<hw>Ply</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Plied</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Plying</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>plien</ets>, F. <ets>plier</ets> to fold, to bend, fr. L.
<ets>plicare</ets>; akin to Gr. <?/, G. <ets>flechten</ets>. Cf.
<er>Apply</er>, <er>Complex</er>, <er>Display</er>, <er>Duplicity</er>,
<er>Employ</er>, <er>Exploit</er>, <er>Implicate</er>, <er>Plait</er>,
<er>Pliant</er>, <er>Flax</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To bend.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As men may warm wax with handes <qex>plie</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To lay on closely, or in folds; to work upon
steadily, or with repeated acts; to press upon; to urge importunately;
<as>as, to <ex>ply</ex> one with questions, with solicitations, or with
drink</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And <qex>plies</qex> him with redoubled strokes</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>plies</qex> the duke at morning and at night.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To employ diligently; to use steadily.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Go <qex>ply</qex> thy needle; meddle not.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To practice or perform with diligence; to work
at.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Their bloody task, unwearied, still they <qex>ply</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Waller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ply</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Ply
<hw>Ply</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To bend; to yield.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It would rather burst atwo than <qex>plye</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The willow <qex>plied</qex>, and gave way to the gust.</q>
<rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To act, go, or work diligently and steadily;
especially, to do something by repeated actions; to go back and forth;
<as>as, a steamer <ex>plies</ex> between certain ports</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ere half these authors be read (which will soon be with
<qex>plying</qex> hard and daily).</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He was forced to <qex>ply</qex> in the streets as a porter.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The heavy hammers and mallets <qex>plied</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To work to windward; to
beat.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ply</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Ply
<hw>Ply</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>pli</ets>, fr.
<ets>plier</ets>. See <er>Ply</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>A fold; a plait; a turn or twist, as of a cord.</def>
<rj><au>Arbuthnot.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Bent; turn; direction; bias.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The late learners can not so well take the <qex>ply</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Boswell, and others of Goldsmith's contemporaries, . . . did not
understand the secret <qex>plies</qex> of his character.</q> <rj><qau>W.
Irving.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The czar's mind had taken a strange <qex>ply</qex>, which it
retained to the last.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Ply</xex> is used in composition to designate
folds, or the number of webs interwoven; as, a three-<xex>ply</xex>
carpet.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plyer</ent>⟦br⟧
